                <h2 class="ctpl-c-faq_header">
                    Frequently Asked Questions
                </h2>

                                    <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-wrapper">
                                <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion ">
                                    <button tabindex="0" area-expanded="false" aria-controls="bb41fe40-3d2d-4830-a2d1-092f60522aeb" id="accordion-id-bb41fe40-3d2d-4830-a2d1-092f60522aeb" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header">
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-content">
                                            Can bonding leave be taken intermittently?
                                        </div>
                                        <div aria-hidden="true" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-button">
                                            <i></i>
                                        </div>
                                    </button>
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-content" id="bb41fe40-3d2d-4830-a2d1-092f60522aeb" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion-id-bb41fe40-3d2d-4830-a2d1-092f60522aeb" tabindex="0">
                                            Bonding leave can only be taken intermittently if approved to be taken that way by the employer.
                                        </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion ">
                                    <button tabindex="0" area-expanded="false" aria-controls="1b992e36-f2f5-4c7c-bdc9-d43eaad958e7" id="accordion-id-1b992e36-f2f5-4c7c-bdc9-d43eaad958e7" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header">
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-content">
                                            If an employer offers 12 weeks of fully paid parental leave, can an employee also apply for CT Paid Leave for 12 weeks after exhausting their employer-offered time?
                                        </div>
                                        <div aria-hidden="true" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-button">
                                            <i></i>
                                        </div>
                                    </button>
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-content" id="1b992e36-f2f5-4c7c-bdc9-d43eaad958e7" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion-id-1b992e36-f2f5-4c7c-bdc9-d43eaad958e7" tabindex="0">
                                            Yes, if the employee has not used any of their 12 weeks of CT Paid Leave benefits they may apply for CT Paid Leave after exhausting any employer-provided benefits. However, if the employee has already exhausted their 12 (or 14) weeks of job protected FMLA leave, they may not be eligible for additional job protected leave.&nbsp;
                                        </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion ">
                                    <button tabindex="0" area-expanded="false" aria-controls="33f9d7bb-acd9-43e0-a37f-5eebe2140163" id="accordion-id-33f9d7bb-acd9-43e0-a37f-5eebe2140163" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header">
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-content">
                                            What does it mean to stand <i>in loco parentis</i> to a child?
                                        </div>
                                        <div aria-hidden="true" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-button">
                                            <i></i>
                                        </div>
                                    </button>
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-content" id="33f9d7bb-acd9-43e0-a37f-5eebe2140163" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion-id-33f9d7bb-acd9-43e0-a37f-5eebe2140163" tabindex="0">
                                            "In loco parentis" means "in the place of the parent".&nbsp; An individual stands <em>in loco parentis</em> to a child if he or she has day-to-day responsibilities to care for or financially support the child and the individual intends to take on the role of a parent to that child or the person in the place of a parent who had such responsibility for the individual when the individual was a child. The person standing <em>in loco parentis</em> is not required to have a biological or legal relationship with the child.<br class="t-last-br" />
                                        </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion ">
                                    <button tabindex="0" area-expanded="false" aria-controls="7eb76fb8-4b95-4418-b700-7a5d7bc3a8f5" id="accordion-id-7eb76fb8-4b95-4418-b700-7a5d7bc3a8f5" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header">
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-content">
                                            Who can receive CT Paid Leave benefits in connection with bonding leave?
                                        </div>
                                        <div aria-hidden="true" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-button">
                                            <i></i>
                                        </div>
                                    </button>
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-content" id="7eb76fb8-4b95-4418-b700-7a5d7bc3a8f5" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion-id-7eb76fb8-4b95-4418-b700-7a5d7bc3a8f5" tabindex="0">
                                            Both the birthing and non-birthing parents may receive CT Paid Leave benefits in connection with bonding leave.&nbsp; (A person who is not a parent and is not standing <em>in loco parentis</em> to the child cannot take bonding leave).
                                        </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion ">
                                    <button tabindex="0" area-expanded="false" aria-controls="ebf82de1-d502-4783-b5d8-59c473d137a0" id="accordion-id-ebf82de1-d502-4783-b5d8-59c473d137a0" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header">
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-content">
                                            Can a grandparent take bonding leave with a new grandchild?
                                        </div>
                                        <div aria-hidden="true" class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-header-button">
                                            <i></i>
                                        </div>
                                    </button>
                                        <div class="ctpl-c-faq_accordion-content" id="ebf82de1-d502-4783-b5d8-59c473d137a0" role="region" aria-labelledby="accordion-id-ebf82de1-d502-4783-b5d8-59c473d137a0" tabindex="0">
                                            No, generally a grandparent cannot take bonding leave to bond with a new grandchild unless the grandparent is standing <em>in loco parentis</em> to the child or is acting as their foster parent.&nbsp;
                                        </div>
                                </div>
                        </div>
        </div>
